<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,858,1531]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1363,1386]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Remarks.</emphasis>
The constricted style apex and short, tapered lateral processes of the theca show this to be a sisterspecies of 
<taxonomicName box="[269,389,1398,1422]" class="Insecta" family="Aphrophoridae" genus="Cephisus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laticeps">
<emphasis box="[269,389,1398,1422]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">C. laticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it may be distinguished by the shorter theca shaft and ventral processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,858,1531]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1434,1459]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Distribution.</emphasis>
Apparently confined to the west coast of the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[972,1061,1434,1458]" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, from just west of Tampico (just south of the Tropic of Cancer) to just south of Villahermosa near the Yucatán Peninsula.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
